                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d121">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">693.002 Manchuria/107: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China (<persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_JNT1"
                            type="from">Johnson</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-06-27T14:00:00+08:00"
                            >June 27, 1932—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received June 27—1:24 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>720. Your 173, June 24, 2 p.m. My British colleague has received instructions
                    similar to yours in paragraph 1. However, he is authorized privately and
                    informally to continue in his conversations with <pb facs="0212" n="114"
                        xml:id="pg_114"/> the Chinese to emphasize the importance of making every
                    effort to prevent the disruption of the Maritime Customs Service.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_JNT1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
